First. Consider moving to jmock (www.jmock.org). That&#39;s our current 
favourite.

You shouldn&#39;t call verify() in the tearDown, it&#39;s just the same as 
calling Assert. The test is over by the time you get to tearDown(), so 
failures won&#39;t be logged properly. In jMock, we&#39;ve subclassed TestCase 
to collect mocks and call verify() automatically in the right place.

S.

cliftonccraig wrote:
&gt; I new to this and I&#39;m not even sure I&#39;m posting to the right list or
&gt; not but here goes. I just started using JUnit and TDD on this project
&gt; I&#39;m working on. I am using MockObjects (I believe .9 version) through
&gt; XDoclet to create a mock of an interface that the object I&#39;m testing
&gt; uses. What I noticed is that introducing the call to mock.verify() in
&gt; the TestCase tearDown method masks exceptions that are thrown from
&gt; test methods. In other words if an unexpected exception occurs in a
&gt; test method it doesn&#39;t appear to show in the logs when the
&gt; mock.verify() executes. Mind you, I am using the JUnit support out of
&gt; IntelliJ Idea. However I don&#39;t think that is relevant to the problem.
&gt; The basics of my TestCase are as follows.
&gt; class MyTestCase
&gt; {
&gt;    private MyMock mock;
&gt; 
&gt;    public void testMyMethod() throws UnExcpectedException
&gt;    {
&gt;       //Test logic here
&gt;    }
&gt;      public void setup()
&gt;    {
&gt;       mock = new MyMock();
&gt;       //logic to set mock preconditions and expectations...
&gt;    }
&gt;      public void verify()
&gt;    {
&gt;       //This executes and thorws an exception that masks the real
&gt; exception in the test method.
&gt;       mock.verify();
&gt;    }
&gt; }
&gt; When I don&#39;t use mocks then I can test and figure out problems rather
&gt; easily because I propogate exceptions up to the JUnit framework where
&gt; the UI catches them and displays them accordingly. I&#39;m not sure if
&gt; this is the best practice which is why I&#39;m writing. Could someone
&gt; guide me here?
